## .NET Performance Review — `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`

**Context:** Hot path — logging framework processing millions of entries/minute.

---

### Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| Sync-over-async | 0 ✅ |
| IndexOf/StartsWith/EndsWith/Contains without `StringComparison` | 0 ✅ |
| `.Substring()` | 0 ✅ |
| `.ToLower()`/`.ToUpper()` | 0 ✅ |
| `.ToLowerInvariant()` | 1 |
| Chained `.Replace()` (3+) | 0 ✅ |
| `params` keyword | 1 (+ 1 comment) |
| LINQ methods (`.Select`/`.Where`/`.Take`/`.Any`/`.Aggregate`) | 17 |
| `.ToArray()` | 1 (+ 2 comments) |
| `.ToList()` | 1 |
| `new List<` | 1 |
| `.ToString()` | 3 actionable |
| `.Trim()` | 1 |
| Unsealed non-abstract classes | 1 of 1 |

---

### 🔴 Critical Findings

#### 1. LINQ Chains on Hot Path (17 instances)

**Impact:** Every LINQ operator (`.Where`, `.Select`, `.Take`, `.Any`, `.Aggregate`) allocates an enumerator + delegate on each call. At millions of calls/min, this generates enormous GC pressure.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L128, L140, L143, L146, L149, L158, L169, L244, L261–262, L270–272, L284, L304

**Fix:** Replace with `foreach` loops and pre-sized lists/arrays. Key rewrites:

`SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` (L133–150) — 3–4 enumerator + 1–2 delegate + 1 list allocation per call:
```csharp
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int count = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (count >= precision) break;
        if (!countEmptyUnits && part == null) continue;
        if (countEmptyUnits) count++;
        if (part != null)
        {
            result.Add(part);
            if (!countEmptyUnits) count++;
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

`IsContainingOnlyNullValue` (L127–128) — enumerator + delegate per call:
```csharp
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```

`ConcatenateTimeSpanParts` (L155–171) — enumerator + delegate + list per call:
```csharp
private static string ConcatenateTimeSpanParts(
    List<string?> timeSpanParts, CultureInfo culture, string collectionSeparator)
{
    int nonNullCount = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeSpanParts)
        if (part != null) nonNullCount++;

    if (nonNullCount == 0) return "no time";
    if (nonNullCount == 1)
    {
        foreach (var part in timeSpanParts)
            if (part != null) return part;
    }

    // Build "A, B and C" format
    var sb = new StringBuilder();
    int idx = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeSpanParts)
    {
        if (part == null) continue;
        idx++;
        if (idx == nonNullCount)
        {
            sb.Append(" and ").Append(part);
        }
        else
        {
            if (idx > 1) sb.Append(collectionSeparator);
            sb.Append(part);
        }
    }
    return sb.ToString();
}
```

`HumanizeDisplayStrings` (L266–286) — 2 enumerators + 2 delegates + array per call:
```csharp
private string HumanizeDisplayStrings(IEnumerable<string?> strings, string separator)
{
    var items = new List<string>();
    foreach (var item in strings)
    {
        var trimmed = item?.Trim();
        if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(trimmed))
            items.Add(trimmed!);
    }

    if (items.Count == 0) return string.Empty;
    if (items.Count == 1) return items[0];

    var sb = new StringBuilder();
    for (int i = 0; i < items.Count - 1; i++)
    {
        if (i > 0) sb.Append(separator);
        sb.Append(items[i]);
    }
    sb.Append(" and ").Append(items[^1]);
    return sb.ToString();
}
```

#### 2. `enum.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` — Compound Allocation (1 instance, called up to 8× per Humanize)

**Impact:** 3 allocations per call: boxing via `ToString()`, the `ToString()` string, then `.ToLowerInvariant()` string. Up to 24 allocations per `Humanize()` call.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175`

**Fix:** Cache unit names in a static array:
```csharp
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
    ["year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = s_unitNames[(int)unit];
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}
```

#### 3. Pointless Allocation in Zero-Value Path (L76)

**Impact:** `CreateTimePartsWithNoTimeValue("no time")[0] ?? "no time"` creates a `List<string?>`, adds one element, indexes it, discards the list — all to return a constant string.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L74–77`, L124–125

**Fix:** Return `"no time"` directly:
```csharp
if (IsContainingOnlyNullValue(timeParts))
    return "no time";
```

---

### 🟡 Moderate Findings

#### 4. `params IStringTransformer[]` Allocates Array Per Call (1 instance)

**Impact:** Every `Transform("...", singleTransformer)` call heap-allocates a `T[]`. The common case is 1 transformer.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L303`

**Fix:** Add a 1-argument overload:
```csharp
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);
```

#### 5. Double `.Select()` Chain in Object Formatter (1 instance)

**Impact:** Two enumerator + two delegate allocations. The `Func<T, object?>` overload chains `.Select(objectFormatter).Select(o => o?.ToString())` when a single `.Select(o => objectFormatter(o)?.ToString())` suffices.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L259–262`

**Fix:** Merge into a single `.Select()`:
```csharp
return HumanizeDisplayStrings(
    collection.Select(o => objectFormatter(o)?.ToString()),
    separator);
```

#### 6. Unsealed Class (1 of 1 classes — 0% sealed)

**Impact:** JIT cannot devirtualize the 4 `virtual` methods. If no subclasses exist, sealing enables inlining.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L208`

**Fix:** Add `sealed` keyword: `public sealed class DefaultCollectionFormatter`

**Caveat:** Only if this class is not subclassed elsewhere. The `virtual` methods suggest intentional extensibility — verify before sealing.

---

### ℹ️ Info

#### 7. Static Initializer Uses `Enumerable.Reverse` + `Enum.GetValues` (L41)

**Impact:** One-time cost at static init — not per-call. But trivially replaceable with a literal.

**Fix:** `private static readonly TimeUnit[] TimeUnits = [TimeUnit.Millisecond, TimeUnit.Second, TimeUnit.Minute, TimeUnit.Hour, TimeUnit.Day, TimeUnit.Week, TimeUnit.Month, TimeUnit.Year];`

---

### ✅ Positive Findings

- ✅ No sync-over-async — no `.Result`, `.Wait()`, or `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`
- ✅ No `Substring()` — no slice-based allocation anti-patterns
- ✅ No chained `.Replace()` calls
- ✅ `List<string?>(8)` pre-sized at L91 — correct capacity hint
- ✅ String interpolation used instead of `string.Format` — avoids boxing

---

### Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| 🔴 Critical | 3 | LINQ chains allocating 10+ objects per `Humanize()` call |
| 🟡 Moderate | 3 | `params` array, double `.Select()`, unsealed class |
| ℹ️ Info | 1 | Static initializer using LINQ (one-time) |

**Estimated per-call allocation savings:** Fixing findings 1–3 eliminates ~30–40 heap allocations per `Humanize()` call. At millions of calls/minute, this is the difference between Gen0 GC pauses being negligible vs. dominating latency.

> ⚠️ **Disclaimer:** These results are generated by an AI assistant and are non-deterministic. Findings may include false positives, miss real issues, or suggest changes that are incorrect for your specific context. Always verify recommendations with benchmarks and human review before applying changes to production code.
